Raised in a mystical word shrouded in secrecy, Donny Hall transcended through a Gozarian time portal to College Station, Texas in the mid 1990's.

Desperate to get back to his alternate dimension, he would work in a subterranean facility on the anecdote to re-open the portal.

Eventually, to blend in with modern society, he was forced to attend a high school in College Station. The kindred spirit of the Evil Thuul God was reborn as a giant geography teaching Slor named Debbie Lange. The battle for Oreo cookies stands still to this day.

In Gozer, Donny (or NYAAAHHHH!!!! as he is called in his home world) felt the same worldly vocation to participate in what you foul humans call "multimedia". He studied and got his game tight. He battled many challenges and won great victories. But every victory has a price...

Today, Donny is far more timid. He works under several contracts for various humanoid media company. He collects many resources including Vespian Gas - a valuable item in other dimensions. 

He wrote all of this in the third person. He grinds like pepper. He's an AirForce stepper. An H-Town repper.

Benjamin Knox is a very diverse and young artist. His interests in nature, history, architecture, music, and sports are exhibited in the many facits of his creative works. Benjamin’s talents go beyond painting and drawing. He also has been involved with the creation of several book projects and is a writer as well. As a building designer, he has a special sensitivity to nature, and the site. He allows time to design one building project per year. He also works with a music producer in Los Angeles, California in developing his musical style that he calls soundscapping- an impassioned atmospheric combination of piano, guitar, voice, and synthesizers. He is now in the learning stages of film development, something that has intrigued him since childhood, and plans to develop those skills more in the future. He feels that he has several unique ideas and creative viewpoints that will have mass appeal in feature films.
Benjamin is a man driven by his passion to create and share with others. He believes that all art forms are inter-connected, and is devoted to a lifetime of developing all of his talents to their full potential.

Joey McGee is a singer songwriter musician poet who recently moved to the Bryan College Station area from Pittsburgh, Pa. You'll experience quite an eclectic sound from Joey, a genre that can best be described as Folk Rock Groove.

M.L. "Sonny" Moss is a native Texan from San Marcos, Texas. After earning his Bachelors Degree in Ceramics from the University of North Florida, in Jacksonville, Florida, "Class of '80", Sonny helped to establish "The Studio", a clay cooperative on Melrose in Avondale with five of his contemporaries.

Upon returning to Texas, he established Mud Creek Pottery, in 1989, in Calvert, Texas, a historic community in rural Robertson County. The studio is now located in one of the many historic buildings in Calvert's historic downtown community. The building, located at 407 S. Main Street, was built circa 1878 and houses the gallery and the studio with the kiln yard behind the main building.

Mud Creek Pottery produces several lines of art pottery that are functionally utilitarian, while appealing to the aesthetic. Sonny currently works with Cone 6 Stoneware, Cone 11 Stoneware, Porcelain, and Raku Firing.

"I am intrigued with the many facets of ceramics, a never-ending myriad of techniques, methods, and materials. The one thing about clay that has always fascinated me is that it is so malleable, formable, responding to and capturing the touch and spirit of the artist, and then, once fired, is forever 'permanent'" -M.L. Moss

The original works of J. Vincent Scarpace (best known for his abstract fish art) represent, in his own words, “a personal journey through the use of basic of art elements: line, shape, and color - resulting in an arrival, just past experimentation, at unique works of art which purposely resemble fish.”  He’s followed his passion for the creative process, discovering that therein may lay the true reason for his next work of art – the pursuit of one’s own creative potential.

J. Vincent knew from an early age exactly what he wanted to do with his life. Born to loving, creative, and supportive parents and family, he was encouraged from about age 2 to pursue line, shape, and color, and the creation of art.  J’s mother, an artist in her own right, taught young J. Vincent how to enjoy drawing, painting, and sculpture very early on. Having a fundamental knowledge of the basic art elements (even before reading and writing, some say) helped J. Vincent to build his own reasons and reality toward eventually deciding that his fate and future was held within the creative process.

J. Vincent’s works have evolved and grown over the years, and he’s paid his dues through a dedication to the pursuit of his passion and the creative process he so believes in.  Having worked as an apprentice, production artist, and studio artist since his age of reason, he’s sacrificed many other worthwhile endeavors in the name of his journey. J. Vincent holds a BS in Education (Art and Mathematics), and after 13 years of teaching (8 years private and 5 years public) he’s retired by choice to his studio to continue his creative journey and drive toward the creation of unique works of abstract fish art. 

Today, J. Vincent Scarpace’s original works can be found in both private and public collections world-wide, in over 40 different countries and in all 50 U.S. States.  He is currently well represented on over 400 websites and online art entities and galleries, in numerous restaurants, and in many corporate and professional venues.

J. Vincent resides in College Station, TX with his beautiful wife Melanie and their very energetic and inquisitive son, Benjamin Vincent, age 4.

Saraart.com ~ Acrylic and Oil Abstracts ~ I would love to paint one for you! If you see a style that you like on my website, but have different colors in mind, I would be happy to create one specifically for you with your color choices in a similar style. Currently all sizes are priced at under $100. 

I am currently a resident of College Station, Tx. I began 
painting in December of 2005 at the age of 29. After a few 
meager attempts several years before with oil, I was 
inspired by a local art exhibit and inquired about the 
different techniques the artist used with acrylics. And now I 
encourage everyone to find the artist inside of themselves 
and keep trying until they find the methods best suited to 
them. Discover your God given gifts and abilities and use 
them!

I have a B.A. in Psychology, a teaching certificate, and am 
a member of the Brazos Valley Art League. I am married to 
a wonderful man and we have a beautiful baby girl.

Greta Watkins is a longtime resident of B/CS, having grown up in College Station. She has owned The Frame Gallery in historic downtown Bryan since 2001. Greta and Sarah, the official greeter and shop dog, really enjoy meeting and assisting customers with their framing projects .

In 2005, Greta instituted "First Fridays @ The Gallery" and helped organize "The Art Step", a semi annual art walk in historic downtown Bryan. Since then, the First Friday event has grown into a monthly event "First Fridays in Historic Downtown Bryan" that involves many of the downtown businesses as well as highlighting the art and culture available in the downtown area.

Also an artist, Greta has concentrated on painting, primarily oils, for the last several years, having previously spent 12 years or so working with handmade paper.
